				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The EC-financed evaluations highlight how EU farmers’ production decisions now largely reflect market price trends, although not market price <i>per se</i>. Production decisions are equally influenced by a reduction in farmer dependence on revenues generated by the sale of crops produced, arising from the effects of the single payment scheme. This more ‘market-oriented’ approach is a direct consequence of the decoupling of support. However, as the durum wheat evaluation pointed out, EU support payments still influence the overall areas placed under cereals crops such as durum wheat.</p><p>The hops sector is somewhat different, with its close connection to trends in the brewing industry making it much more market driven. Overall however EU production is shifting to what markets demand rather than what specific production subsidies encourage. Nevertheless, the area under crops and overall production are strongly influenced by the overall level of public sector support extended via the single farm payment. This being stated, EU policies are increasingly being designed to reduce the impact of price instability on the agricultural base, while patterns of agricultural production across the EU are shifting towards those areas most suited to the production of specific crops. Broad underlying policy objectives are thus being attained, even if all specific objectives have not yet been attained. As a result, farmers’ leaders are far from happy with the effectiveness of EU ‘safety net’ policies and are pressing for additional measures.</p><p>The long-term implications of these developments for the ACP-EU trade relationship are far from clear. With regard to cereals sector development, perhaps one of the most important areas of impact relates to the relative attractiveness of cereals and sugar beet production for EU farmers. If cereals production becomes more attractive to EU farmers, the transition to a production-quota free EU sugar regime would be facilitated. This could create a situation where national sugar production quotas are removed without any need for a further reduction in the EU reference price for sugar.</p><p>What is clear is that with the shift to decoupled support, production patterns within the EU will increasingly be driven by the relative prices of different agricultural commodities on EU markets, and not the different levels of product-specific aid available under EU support schemes. This implies a need for increased flexibility and market responsiveness of the part of ACP producers and traders, as EU prices fluctuate in the light of global and EU production and price trends.</p>
		</div>
		
